WEBVTT	#Elemental Media Engine(TM) 2.17.0.0

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.430
The Biden administration has relocated

00:00:02.430 --> 00:00:04.770
the final group of Afghan evacuees

00:00:04.770 --> 00:00:06.820
from a New Jersey military base.

00:00:06.820 --> 00:00:10.020
The effort ends the first stage of a massive month

00:00:10.020 --> 00:00:12.540
long resettlement operation following

00:00:12.540 --> 00:00:14.670
the collapse of the, now, Taliban

00:00:14.670 --> 00:00:16.380
controlled Afghan government.

00:00:16.380 --> 00:00:19.950
76,000 Afghans have already relocated

00:00:19.950 --> 00:00:22.500
to their new communities in the US.

00:00:22.500 --> 00:00:24.990
According to information obtained by CBS News,

00:00:24.990 --> 00:00:27.900
nearly half of the 67,000 Afghans,

00:00:27.900 --> 00:00:32.070
processed at domestic bases, have settled in these states.

00:00:32.070 --> 00:00:35.610
Another 21,000 have settled in 17 other states

00:00:35.610 --> 00:00:37.260
and that number could grow.

00:00:37.260 --> 00:00:39.570
Wyoming is the only state not expected

00:00:39.570 --> 00:00:41.430
to receive any evacuees.

00:00:41.430 --> 00:00:44.880
CBS News immigration reporter, Camilo Montoya Galvez,

00:00:44.880 --> 00:00:46.690
is here with me now.

00:00:46.690 --> 00:00:47.610
Hi, Camilo.

00:00:47.610 --> 00:00:49.950
Officials say that this resettlement operation

00:00:49.950 --> 00:00:51.650
is the largest in US history.

00:00:51.650 --> 00:00:52.320
Is that correct?

00:00:52.320 --> 00:00:55.140
Can you tell us how many have been resettled so far?

00:00:55.140 --> 00:00:56.040
Where they're going?

00:00:56.040 --> 00:01:00.160
And why is Wyoming not on that list?

00:01:00.160 --> 00:01:03.180
This is certainly the largest evacuation and resettlement

00:01:03.180 --> 00:01:06.750
operation by the US government since 1975,

00:01:06.750 --> 00:01:09.030
When the US resettled tens of thousands

00:01:09.030 --> 00:01:12.240
of Vietnamese refugees following the fall of Saigon.

00:01:12.240 --> 00:01:16.710
So far, as you mentioned, 76,000 of these Afghan evacuees

00:01:16.710 --> 00:01:20.670
have been resettled in over 200 communities across the US.

00:01:20.670 --> 00:01:24.120
Many of them were processed at these military installations

00:01:24.120 --> 00:01:27.630
where they underwent vaccination against the coronavirus

00:01:27.630 --> 00:01:30.820
and other diseases, as well as immigration paperwork.

00:01:30.820 --> 00:01:34.080
We know that half of the evacuees process

00:01:34.080 --> 00:01:36.270
at these military installations have

00:01:36.270 --> 00:01:40.200
resettled in eight states, including Texas and California.

00:01:40.200 --> 00:01:43.470
Another dozen states have received each more than 1,000

00:01:43.470 --> 00:01:44.160
evacuees.

00:01:44.160 --> 00:01:46.980
And, as you mentioned, Wyoming is the only state

00:01:46.980 --> 00:01:50.330
that we understand is not set to receive any evacuees.

00:01:50.330 --> 00:01:52.830
Is that because state officials have said, we don't want any

00:01:52.830 --> 00:01:53.340
evacuees?

00:01:53.340 --> 00:01:54.300
Or why is that?

00:01:54.300 --> 00:01:57.690
It's unclear, but there is not the same resettlement

00:01:57.690 --> 00:02:00.990
infrastructure in that state compared to these larger

00:02:00.990 --> 00:02:01.650
states.

00:02:01.650 --> 00:02:03.600
We know you'll dig into that answer.

00:02:03.600 --> 00:02:05.610
We know that top FEMA official, Bob Fenton,

00:02:05.610 --> 00:02:07.800
has been leading these resettlement efforts.

00:02:07.800 --> 00:02:09.810
You spoke with Fenton.

00:02:09.810 --> 00:02:11.400
What did he tell you?

00:02:11.400 --> 00:02:14.460
Bob Fenton, who is a DHS official overseeing

00:02:14.460 --> 00:02:16.440
this effort, said that this is the largest

00:02:16.440 --> 00:02:18.030
operation of its kind.

00:02:18.030 --> 00:02:22.770
Again, these evacuees needed culturally appropriate food,

00:02:22.770 --> 00:02:26.520
faith services, vaccination, medical services,

00:02:26.520 --> 00:02:29.730
legal assistance to file applications for work permits

00:02:29.730 --> 00:02:31.410
and asylum applications.

00:02:31.410 --> 00:02:33.900
And so, he likened these military bases

00:02:33.900 --> 00:02:36.220
to eight small cities.

00:02:36.220 --> 00:02:39.870
Let's hear some of your interview with him.

00:02:39.870 --> 00:02:41.490
I think this population is special.

00:02:41.490 --> 00:02:45.800
These are individuals that work for the United States

00:02:45.800 --> 00:02:50.210
and support our military . in war over the last decade.

00:02:50.210 --> 00:02:52.230
There's a lot of unique stories.

00:02:52.230 --> 00:02:54.350
I've had the opportunity to walk through the bases,

00:02:54.350 --> 00:02:55.970
hear these stories.

00:02:55.970 --> 00:03:01.350
I met a woman who's resettling to Minnesota that looks forward

00:03:01.350 --> 00:03:03.020
to being a teacher there and giving back

00:03:03.020 --> 00:03:04.010
to the United States.

00:03:04.010 --> 00:03:07.920
Many of these people want to enter our communities.

00:03:07.920 --> 00:03:09.860
They want to be accepted.

00:03:09.860 --> 00:03:14.390
Just amazing to walk among the kids and see the smiles

00:03:14.390 --> 00:03:18.200
and have led a very vulnerable life.

00:03:18.200 --> 00:03:22.490
We, as Americans, need to help accept them

00:03:22.490 --> 00:03:27.350
in, help them get situated, and welcome to the United States.

00:03:27.350 --> 00:03:29.270
So Bob Fenton is very welcoming.

00:03:29.270 --> 00:03:32.750
Do we know if the majority of Americans feel as welcoming?

00:03:32.750 --> 00:03:34.640
Polling does seem to indicate, Tanya,

00:03:34.640 --> 00:03:37.940
that a majority of Americans support helping and resettling

00:03:37.940 --> 00:03:42.310
Afghans who directly assisted US military forces during the year

00:03:42.310 --> 00:03:43.820
old war in Afghanistan.

00:03:43.820 --> 00:03:46.520
And, to be frank, this is a rare immigration policy

00:03:46.520 --> 00:03:48.950
that has garnered bipartisan support, including

00:03:48.950 --> 00:03:50.810
from Republicans in Congress.

00:03:50.810 --> 00:03:53.120
However, some conservative Republicans

00:03:53.120 --> 00:03:56.990
have expressed concern about the way these evacuees were vetted

00:03:56.990 --> 00:03:59.480
and screened, but the Biden administration

00:03:59.480 --> 00:04:01.970
has maintained that all of these evacuees

00:04:01.970 --> 00:04:06.050
went through rigorous vetting at overseas military installations

00:04:06.050 --> 00:04:08.030
before reaching US soil.

00:04:08.030 --> 00:04:10.400
We also know, according to a government report that we

00:04:10.400 --> 00:04:12.860
obtained, that several evacuees were

00:04:12.860 --> 00:04:16.070
barred from entering the US after red flags were

00:04:16.070 --> 00:04:17.540
raised during processing.

00:04:17.540 --> 00:04:20.190
And Camilo, you talked to Fenton about a variety of things,

00:04:20.190 --> 00:04:22.940
including how these refugees are getting

00:04:22.940 --> 00:04:25.350
acclimated to a new normal.

00:04:25.350 --> 00:04:27.560
Let's listen to what he said.

00:04:27.560 --> 00:04:28.980
One of the things we're focused on

00:04:28.980 --> 00:04:34.020
was safety of, not only the Afghan population,

00:04:34.020 --> 00:04:36.150
but communities in the United States.

00:04:36.150 --> 00:04:39.120
To ensure that all the age appropriate vaccinations were

00:04:39.120 --> 00:04:43.800
provided to our guests as they evacuated was important.

00:04:43.800 --> 00:04:46.620
Plus, doing all the screening and vetting overseas and again

00:04:46.620 --> 00:04:49.310
at our ports of entry to ensure of who we were letting

00:04:49.310 --> 00:04:53.130
in the United States and that, from a security standpoint,

00:04:53.130 --> 00:04:56.840
we were making good decisions in that respect.

00:04:56.840 --> 00:04:59.010
Camilo, what other obstacles are both the government

00:04:59.010 --> 00:05:01.320
and these Afghan refugees facing?

00:05:01.320 --> 00:05:04.950
One major obstacle, Tanya, is that many of these evacuees

00:05:04.950 --> 00:05:07.260
could find themselves in legal limbo.

00:05:07.260 --> 00:05:09.750
For all intents and purposes, these evacuees

00:05:09.750 --> 00:05:12.450
are refugees because they fled a war zone.

00:05:12.450 --> 00:05:14.850
However, legally they are not refugees

00:05:14.850 --> 00:05:17.820
because they do not enter through the traditional US

00:05:17.820 --> 00:05:18.870
refugee program.

00:05:18.870 --> 00:05:21.630
The Biden administration authorized their entry

00:05:21.630 --> 00:05:25.080
through another classification, known as humanitarian parole.

00:05:25.080 --> 00:05:27.480
Parole allows them to live and work here legally,

00:05:27.480 --> 00:05:29.430
but it does not offer them a pathway

00:05:29.430 --> 00:05:30.980
to permanent legal status.

00:05:30.980 --> 00:05:33.150
So their paperwork is tricky, is what you're saying?

00:05:33.150 --> 00:05:34.780
They're going to have to go through all

00:05:34.780 --> 00:05:36.070
these legal hurdles?

00:05:36.070 --> 00:05:36.570
Correct.

00:05:36.570 --> 00:05:39.420
Unless Congress moves to legalize them,

00:05:39.420 --> 00:05:42.270
as the Biden administration has proposed,

00:05:42.270 --> 00:05:45.270
these evacuees will not have a permanent pathway

00:05:45.270 --> 00:05:46.020
to US citizenship.

00:05:46.020 --> 00:05:47.820
Will they not be able to work here, then?

00:05:47.820 --> 00:05:50.400
They will be able to work here and live here

00:05:50.400 --> 00:05:54.120
for up to two years and they can renew that classification,

00:05:54.120 --> 00:05:55.020
called parole.

00:05:55.020 --> 00:05:58.200
But again, they cannot have access to green cards right now

00:05:58.200 --> 00:06:02.220
and, ultimately, US citizenship, unless they apply for asylum

00:06:02.220 --> 00:06:03.510
and win asylum.

00:06:03.510 --> 00:06:05.430
But, the asylum program currently

00:06:05.430 --> 00:06:08.800
has over 400,000 unresolved applications.

00:06:08.800 --> 00:06:11.010
Many challenges, but I'm sure they wouldn't change it

00:06:11.010 --> 00:06:11.950
for anything.

00:06:11.950 --> 00:06:12.450
Right?

00:06:12.450 --> 00:06:14.490
You've spoken to some families that are happy to be here.

00:06:14.490 --> 00:06:15.060
Correct?

00:06:15.060 --> 00:06:15.630
Yes.

00:06:15.630 --> 00:06:18.330
We spoke to an Afghan evacuee who

00:06:18.330 --> 00:06:21.090
said he used to work at an American military base

00:06:21.090 --> 00:06:23.910
in Afghanistan before the Taliban takeover.

00:06:23.910 --> 00:06:26.610
He was brought to the US alongside his wife

00:06:26.610 --> 00:06:28.320
and their three minor children.

00:06:28.320 --> 00:06:31.020
They are now living in an apartment in Northern Virginia

00:06:31.020 --> 00:06:33.510
listed by Airbnb, which has actually set up

00:06:33.510 --> 00:06:35.650
a program to house evacuees.

00:06:35.650 --> 00:06:37.770
They're hoping to move to a more permanent location

00:06:37.770 --> 00:06:38.790
in the coming days.

00:06:38.790 --> 00:06:40.980
After that, he told me that he will

00:06:40.980 --> 00:06:45.390
seek to enroll his children in school and try to find work.

00:06:45.390 --> 00:06:47.280
He said the children love Virginia

00:06:47.280 --> 00:06:48.810
and they love going to the park.

00:06:48.810 --> 00:06:51.810
But, he did express concern about the family's

00:06:51.810 --> 00:06:53.010
legal status.

00:06:53.010 --> 00:06:56.490
He mentioned that he hopes Congress and the US government

00:06:56.490 --> 00:06:59.620
will provide them some certainty in the coming months.

00:06:59.620 --> 00:07:01.290
Camilo Montoya Galvez, thank you so much

00:07:01.290 --> 00:07:02.830
for your excellent reporting on this.

00:07:02.830 --> 00:07:04.550
We appreciate it.